vided by Prussia and the empire but because these regimes understood and utilized it as a capital city. It became an imperial city and then a legendary European metropolis in a rather indirect way. This volume examines the relationship between capital city and state, as well as the independent role that Berlin had as a flourishing center of business and finance.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aFinanzgeschichte. 4aKommunal- und Infrastrukturgeschichte. 4aMetropolenforschung. 4aWirtschaftsgeschichte. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aEconomic history.  acity and infrastructure history.  afinance history.  ametropolitan research.1 aHistorische Kommission, , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLandesarchiv Berlin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb0 cEPUBz97831111787690 cprintz978311117820240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783111178714zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111178714zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111178714/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA